<h1>To Robert Dinwiddie</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Hble Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">March 7th 1754 Belvoir</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>If the Vessel your Honour hird of Colo. Eyre<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> has not left York, or Mr Carlyles Norfolk and Hampton We should be glad to have as many Tints sent up as can be spard, for there is no proper Linnen to make them of here and would be difficult to
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-01-02-pb-0072">[72]</span>
get done if there was[.] We also are much in want of Cutlasses, Halbards, Officers half Pikes, Drums &amp;ca which I am informd are in the Magazine that Drum which was sent up with the Artillery being very bad is scarcely worth the trouble of carrying.</p>
<p>The generality of those Men, who have enlisted for this Expedition are much in want of, and press greatly for Cloathings[.] They all desire so earnestly to be put into a Uniform dress that they would gladly do it at their own Expence to be deducted out of their Pay it was the greatest objection to enlisting and many have refusd solely on that account after coming purposely to do it with Expectation of getting a Regimental Sute and if I may be so bold to offer my Opinion I cant think<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> but the good Effects that it may produce will sufficiently recompense for any trouble that will ensue. It is the Nature of Indians to be struck with, and taken by show and this will give them a much higher Conception of our Power and greatness and I verily believe fix in our Interest many that are now wavering and undetermind whose Cause to EspouseIf it was only a Coat of the Coursest red which may be had in these parts it would answer the Intentionred with them is compard to Blood and is lookd upon as the distinguishing marks of Warriours and great MenThe shabby and ragged appearance the French common Soldiers make affords great matter for ridicule amongst the Indians and I really believe is the chief motive why they hate and despise them as they do. If these are the Effects, the Cause may be easily, and timely remedied. I hope Your Honour will pardon this freedom, which I should not have assumd but with a good Intention It is my acquaintance with these Indians, and a Study of their Tempers that has in some measure let me into their Customs and dispositions.</p>
<p>There is another thing the Soldiers enquire much about i,e, who is to be pay Master and the time for payment Your Honours answer to this will oblige me very much as I may thereby satisfie the doubts which arrise on that Head[.]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> I am with all due respect Yr Honours most Obt Humble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0036-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr> (facsimile), University of Kentucky Library <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Bulletin</span>, no. 20 (1960).
 Sotheby Parke Bernet Catalogue no. 2 (sale of manuscripts belonging to Philip Sang), item 587, sold 14 Nov. 1978. Both of these sources contain partial facsimiles.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-01-02-pb-0073">[73]</span>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>This was probably Littleton Eyre (d. 1768), county lieutenant and burgess for Northampton County, who owned several sailing ships plying Chesapeake Bay.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The text to this point is taken from the facsimile in the University of Kentucky Library <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Bulletin</span>; the remainder of the text is taken from the facsimile in the Sotheby Parke Bernet catalogue.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0036-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>At a meeting of the council on 14 Mar. 1754, Dinwiddie laid before the Board two letters from Major Washington, One of the third and the other of the seventh of March from Belvoir purporting that the men inlisted press greatly for Cloathing and that he shall be reduced to great Streights, unless he receives a Speedy Supply of Money. Whereupon it was the Advice of the Council that his Honour would dispatch a Trusty Messenger to the Treasurer for Money and if there should not be Sufficient in his Hands, apply to the Receiver General and borrow Three Hundred Pounds out of the Revenue of two shillings per Hogshead &amp;c. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ H. R. McIlwaine et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Executive Journals of the Council of Colonial Virginia&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Richmond, 192566. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Exec. Journals of Virginia Council</span></span>, 5:46364).</p>

</div>
